Name: n-Dodecane
Description: Dodecane is a straight-chain alkane with 12 carbon atoms. It has been isolated from the essential oils of various plants including Zingiber officinale (ginger). It has a role as a plant metabolite.

animal_concentrations.References: (1) Carril Gonzalez-Barros ST et al; Chemosphere 36: 597-602 (1998) (2) Taylor DL et al; Marine Poll Bull 20: 465-68 (1989) (3) Seagars DJ, Garlich-Miller J; Mar Pollut Bull 43: 122-131 (2001)
animal_concentrations.Value: The concentration of dodecane in tissue samples collected from 12 wolves of Northern Spain was determined to be 1.89, 3.26, 11.01, 90.44, and 6.71 mg/kg lipid weight in spleens, livers, muscle, kidney and suprarenal capsules, respectively(1). The concentration of dodecane in blubber collected from walruses (Odobenus rosmarus divergens) in six locations of the Pacific Ocean was determined to range from 0 to 0.07 ppm wet weight(2). Dodecane was detected in the blubber of Pacific walruses at a mean concentration of 0.06 ug/g wet weight and a range of 0.01 to 0.16 ug/g wet weight. Samples were collected from 8 males and 19 females from the Bering Sea in 1991(3).

fish_seafood_concentrations.References: (1) Al-Saad HT; Marine Pollut Bull 21: 155-57 (1990) (2) Brown DW et al; Investigation of Petroleum in the Marine Environs of the Strait of Juan de Fuca and Northern Puget Sound; p.107 USEPA-600/7-79-164 (1979) (3) Quintero S, Diaz C; Marine Pollut Bull 28: 44-49 (1994) (4) Winger PV et al; Arch Environ Contam Toxicol 19: 101-17 (1990)
fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Thirteen species of fish collected from the Arabian Gulf during 1985 were found to contain dodecane concentrations in muscle ranging from 0.1 to 0.4 ug/g dry weight(1). Mussels from Puget Sound (March Point) were found to contain dodecane in concentrations ranging from 79-360 ppb(2). The concentration of dodecane identified in the fish species Boops boops, Scomber japonicus, and Sardina pilchardus collected near the Canary Islands was determined to be 990, 482, and 325 ng/g wet weight, respectively(3). The mean concentration of dodecane in channel catfish (Ictalurus punctatus), bowfin (Amia calva), white catfish (I. catus), fiddler crab (Uca pugilator), and sea catfish (Arius felis) collected from the Savannah River, Georgia/South Carolina between February 1984 and August 1985 ranged from not detected to 0.02 ug/g wet weight(4).

sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENT: Sediment collected from Puget Sound (March Point) in February 1977 was found to contain dodecane in concentrations ranging from 2.5-4.8 ppb(1).
